title: [RIP] 820-3476 green & red light no fan
message:
I have a 3476 that had some liquid damage/corrosion under the U7200 which I replaced. Here some measurements: 

PPBUS_G3H  =  12.57
PP3V42_G3H = 3.42
PPVRTC_G3H = 3.34
PP5V_S5  =  5.02
PP5V_S4  =  0
PP3V3_S5  = 3.34
PP3V3_S4  =  0.45
PPVCC_S0_CPU = Pulsing from 0 - 0.59

U7501
Pin 12 SMC_PM_G2_EN = 3.42  
Pin 21 S5_PWR_EN = 3.42 
Pin 23 VIN = 12.57
P5VS4RS3_EN  =  0

The PP5V_S0 Line goes from 0 to 5v and then turn off again. 
U6100 checked seems OK, resistor and power going in same for U1950
Found a short in PPVCC_S0_CPU seems to be a trouble to test all C :P any ideas?

title: [RIP] 820-3476 green & red light no fan
message: It is power cycling. What is resistance to GND on PVCC_S0_CPU?

title: [RIP] 820-3476 green & red light no fan
message: There is none its shorted as mentioned above.

title: [RIP] 820-3476 green & red light no fan
message:
PPVCC_S0_CPU = Pulsing from 0 - 0.59

So no way it is fully shorted. Again, what is the resistance to GND?

title: [RIP] 820-3476 green & red light no fan
message:
Hi Duke,

I wrote -> "The PP5V_S0 Line goes from 0 to 5v and then turn off again", this measured on the fan's 5V pin

The PPVCC_S0_CPU gives me 0.06 and a beep when measuring resistance to ground

title: [RIP] 820-3476 green & red light no fan
message: oh yes i forgot i measured that too that is correct its pulsing as well, and when I measure Short to GND I get a beep and 0.055 or 6

title: [RIP] 820-3476 green & red light no fan
message: I only have a 2.6 board here to compare but a good 2.6 CPU measures 80 Ohm to GND on CPU Vcore. You measured diode mode but at 0.05 that will pretty much be the same in Ohm. o very likely the CPU is fried.
